Verbose Response: 

1. A fully automated homelab deployment (Ansible + Proxmox/ESXi/Hyper-V)
Signals: automation mindset, virtualization, config management, repeatability
Cost: $0 if you already run Proxmox or similar

What you build:

A GitHub repo containing an Ansible playbook that spins up and configures a set of VMs
Automated provisioning of services (DNS, monitoring, logging agent, backup jobs, user accounts, updates)
Documented architecture diagram + README

2. A mini enterprise monitoring stack (Prometheus + Grafana + Loki + Alertmanager)
Signals: observability, metrics, logging, infrastructure understanding
Cost: free, uses containers

What you build:

A lightweight, production-style monitoring stack running in Docker or Podman
Exporters on your VMs for CPU, disk, uptime, journald logs, etc.
Dashboards that show real operational insight
Alerting rules (email, Discord, Slack)
The deliverable is a repo + screenshots showing you understand real systems health.

3. A secure lab network with VLAN segmentation and policy-based routing
Signals: networking, security, homelab architecture, practical real-world setups
Cost: uses your existing router/switch or something like OPNsense/pfSense

What you build:

A multi-VLAN network (home, lab, DMZ, IoT)
Firewall rules separating them
Optional: WireGuard VPN into your lab
Network diagram + documentation
This shows you’re comfortable with enterprise-style network design.

4. A centralized identity + SSO lab (FreeIPA, Keycloak, AD DS)
Signals: identity management, authentication flows, IAM
Cost: free with open-source components

Possible goal:

Stand up FreeIPA or Samba AD
Integrate Keycloak for SSO
Connect apps (Grafana, Gitea, Vaultwarden, Nextcloud)
Document user provisioning and policies
Hiring managers love seeing IAM experience because it’s real operational complexity.

5. A backup + disaster recovery system with automated restores
Signals: reliability engineering, planning, scripting, systems admin maturity
Cost: free software like Borg, Restic, Kopia, or PBS

What you build:

Automated per-host backups
Off-site copy (could be just another machine in a different room)
A documented “restore from zero” process
Validated restore tests
This is extremely high-signal because most junior devs never think about backups.

6. A full “company-in-a-box” environment
This is a way to show broad systems experience.

You build a small but realistic IT environment with:

Directory service
Centralized logging
Monitoring
Ticketing (like OpenProject or Zammad)
Basic CI/CD or automation
Backups
Maybe an internal wiki
It’s like building the minimum viable infrastructure of a tech company.
